<section class="block-section story">
  <span class="section-tag">📖 Story</span>
  <h2>Why this block matters</h2>
  <p class="sub">Ten blocks ago: four unlabelled planets and a list of guesses. Today: a verdict, defended.</p>
  <p>The unit's anchor question was <em>is Earth special, or is it one of many habitable planets we just haven't found yet?</em> You don't answer that in the abstract — you answer it through your chosen exoplanet, your framework, and your willingness to defend a verdict when classmates push back. Today is the day your work meets an audience.</p>
  <p>The Stakeholder Q&A format matters. Peers play a <strong>NASA evaluation committee</strong> with limited deep-observation time available. Each verdict is a recommendation for where to point the next observation. Sometimes the strongest verdict isn't the most enthusiastic one — it's the one that names its uncertainty honestly and tells the committee exactly what data would change its mind. This is the same format you'll use in every later summative: U3 Engineering Defense, U4 Climate Brief panel, U5 Stakeholder Roundtable, U6 Planning Board, U7 Public Op-Ed.</p>
  <p>After the Q&A, we close the unit. One reflection circle. One look back at the "I used to think life needed ___" sentence from Block 1. Then a five-minute look forward — Unit 2 (Surface Processes) takes the geosphere subsystem you sketched in Block 2 and goes deep.</p>
</section>

