<section class="block-section do">
  <span class="section-tag">🛠️ Do</span>
  <h2>Today's work — the structured 80 minutes</h2>
  <p class="sub">Not a choice — every student goes through every phase. The whole class is the NASA Evaluation Committee.</p>
  <div class="choice-intro">
    <strong>Learning Intention:</strong> I can defend my framework classifications under sustained questioning and revise my position when given strong counter-evidence.
  </div>
  <div class="choice-board">
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">1</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Submit + bell ringer (10 min)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Goldilocks Reports and AI Documentation submitted via Google Classroom at the start of class — no late submissions; the verdict you defend has to be the one that's been scored. While submissions are being checked, the JWST spectrum prompt is on screen for a quick whole-class discussion.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">2</div>
      <div class="choice-title">NASA Committee Q&A round (55 min)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Each student pitches their verdict in 3–4 minutes, then takes ≥2 peer questions over 2 minutes. Peers play the NASA evaluation committee. The Q&A Bank gives six categories questioners draw from — vary your category across the round: <strong>Clarification</strong> (what did you mean by…?), <strong>Evidence + source</strong> (what's your source for that?), <strong>Trade-off / comparative</strong> (why this exoplanet over Mars or TRAPPIST-1e?), <strong>Uncertainty</strong> (what's your biggest unknown?), <strong>Implementation / observation</strong> (what would you point JWST at?), <strong>Devil's-advocate</strong> (convince me the science return justifies the cost). Be substantive, not gotcha. Acknowledge good answers. If a presenter says "I don't know," don't pile on — that's a strong answer.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">3</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Unit reflection circle (10 min)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Whole-class circle. One question: <em>What's the most important thing you now know about Earth that you didn't four weeks ago?</em> One-sentence answer per student. No commentary. The point is to surface the spread of what 25 brains carry out of this unit.</div>
    </div>
    <div class="choice">
      <div class="choice-letter">4</div>
      <div class="choice-title">Connect-forward to Unit 2 (5 min)</div>
      <div class="choice-detail">Brief preview: the geosphere subsystem you sketched in Block 2 becomes Unit 2's main subject. Same systems-thinking lens, applied close to home — weathering, erosion, deposition, and the surface processes that shape habitable land. The audience-defense format you practiced today is the format you'll use in every subsequent unit summative.</div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

